    "(27)Therefore, Equation ( 27) was used to select a single value of ∆ that guarantees, in combination with Equation (19), that the empirical correlation between each turbine and the farm-level penetration remains strictly above the prescribed threshold R max across all simulated scenarios, while preserving strong coupling through the common factor P farm.The complete sampling procedure for a single penetration scenario can be summarized as follows: (i) compute ∆ from Equation ( 27) using the prescribed R max; (ii) draw a farmlevel penetration P (s) farm according to Equation ( 20); (iii) draw deviations ε (s) i according to Equation (21); and (iv) form P (s) i for all turbines using Equation (19).From a probabilistic standpoint, the penetration model above was embedded into the broader Monte Carlo framework used to generate the fault scenarios.",
    "Each scenario s was characterized by the joint random tuple:(s) = P, D (s) R (s) f, ϕ (s),(28)where (s) = [P (s) 1,..., PNWT] ⊤ is the penetration vector generated as described above, F (s) is the fault type, D (s) is the fault location, Rf is the fault resistance, and ϕ (s) is the fault inception angle.",
    "The combinations of discrete parameters considered in this work were summarized in Table III.TABLE III PARAMETERS AND VALUES USED TO GENERATE THE SCENARIOS.",
